{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:02:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15864"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8555"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"8584"},{"type":"tags","id":"8690"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20525"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring oogenesis, the primary oocyte undergoes two meiotic divisions to produce a mature ovum. This process involves the formation of polar bodies through unequal cell division to preserve cytoplasmic volume in the developing egg cell.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the chromosomal content of polar bodies during oogenesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First polar body contains 23 duplicated chromosomes, second contains 23 single chromosomes","First polar body contains 46 duplicated chromosomes, second contains 46 single chromosomes","First polar body contains 23 single chromosomes, second contains 46 single chromosomes","First polar body contains 46 single chromosomes, second contains 23 single chromosomes","First polar body contains 23 single chromosomes, second contains 23 duplicated chromosomes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring oogenesis, two unequal cell divisions occur to produce polar bodies. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst polar body contains 23 duplicated chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E and forms during meiosis I when the primary oocyte divides. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond polar body contains 23 single chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E and forms during meiosis II when the secondary oocyte divides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst polar body contains 46 duplicated chromosomes, second contains 46 single chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This would represent double the actual chromosome number\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst polar body contains 23 single chromosomes, second contains 46 single chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - The chromosomes are still duplicated in the first polar body\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst polar body contains 46 single chromosomes, second contains 23 single chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This misrepresents both the number and state of chromosomes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst polar body contains 23 single chromosomes, second contains 23 duplicated chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This reverses the correct chromosome states\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolar bodies are a mechanism to dispose of excess chromosomes while maintaining maximum cytoplasmic volume in the developing egg cell. They eventually degenerate and do not contribute to embryo formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Polar bodies are small cells produced during oogenesis that contain discarded chromosomes to ensure the ovum retains maximum cytoplasm.","The first polar body forms during meiosis I and contains 23 duplicated chromosomes.","The second polar body forms during meiosis II and contains 23 single chromosomes.","Polar bodies eventually degenerate and do not contribute to embryo formation."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T21:35:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T21:36:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8555"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identify